  "content_en": "<div class=\"royal-legacy-card\"><div class=\"legacy-section\"><div class=\"legacy-section-header\"><span class=\"legacy-icon\"> üïâÔ∏è</span><h5>Patronage of Brahmanical Culture</h5></div><div class=\"legacy-section-content\"><p>Like the Shungas, the Kanvas were Brahmans and continued to patronize Vedic religion and culture. Despite the turbulent political climate, they played a role in preserving Sanskrit language and traditional education. This period witnessed the compilation of 'Smriti' texts and the consolidation of social norms.</p></div></div><div class=\"legacy-section\"><div class=\"legacy-section-header\"><span class=\"legacy-icon\"> ‚öîÔ∏è</span><h5>Political Transition</h5></div><div class=\"legacy-section-content\"><p>The end of Kanva rule coincided with the rise of the Satavahanas (Andhras). This marked a significant historical turning point as it signified the end of North India's (Magadha's) political supremacy and the rise of Deccan's power. After the fall of the Kanvas, Magadha remained politically fragmented for several centuries until the advent of the Gupta Empire.</p></div></div><div class=\"legacy-section\"><div class=\"legacy-section-header\"><span class=\"legacy-icon\"> üé®</span><h5>Art and Architecture</h5></div><div class=\"legacy-section-content\"><p>Although no grand architectural remnants of the Kanvas themselves survive, it is believed that artistic activities at Sanchi and Bharhut continued during their time, depicting both Buddhist and Brahmanical themes.</p></div></div></div>"
